<h1 align="center"> 4.  MOTIONS IN THE SKY  </h1>

<p><br></p>

<center><a href="im/startrails-over-Himalayas-AJankovoy.jpg"><img src="im/startrails-over-Himalayas-AJankovoy-sm.jpg" width=80%></a></center>

<p align="right"><small><em> Star trails over the Himalayas in a<br> 2-hour exposure
<a href="http://jankovoy.livejournal.com/">(Anton Jankovoy)</a>.
</em></small>   

<p><br></p>

<b>Cyclical</b> motions of bright objects in sky were the <b>main
historical stimulus</b> for the study of astronomy.  The motions became
the subject of intensive study by many ancient cultures, even if they
could not interpret the motions properly.  Ultimately, analysis of these
motions led to some of the most important developments in
the history of modern science.  In this guide, we describe some of these
motions as they might have been seen by ancient astronomers but
explain them from a modern perspective.</p>

<p><br></p>

<h2>A. Motions of Bright Objects </p></h2>

The table below lists celestial motions which are easily detectable by
someone on the Earth without telescopes.  </p>

