The best way to visualize celestial motions is in a planetarium or
with a good computer sky simulation program.  We will use
the <em><a href="http://www.siennasoft.com"> Starry Night</a></em>
simulator in class.</p>

But a faster way to experience the diurnal motion is to view one of
the many excellent <a href="1210links.html#videos"><b>time-lapse
videos</b></a> now available on the Web.</p>

</ul>

Celestial motions may be complicated, but they are <b>repeatable</b>
over periods of months to years, and their <b>cyclic nature</b> was quickly
recognized by many cultures.  It was this feature that encouraged
people to search for a deeper understanding of them, especially in
view of what they might portend for themselves. </p>

The cycles also naturally became the basis of practical 
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calendar"><b>calendar
systems</b></a>.  For instance, Western calendars are based on 7-day <b>weeks</b>
(one day for each of the bright moving lights in the sky: the Sun,
Moon, and five planets), 30-day <b>months</b> (one lunar cycle),
and 365-day <b>years</b> (one cycle of the Sun in motion against
the stars).  </p>

</ul>


